   "source": [
    "# Relationship between continental-scale patterns of fire activity and modes of climate variability \n",
    "\n",
    "Geocomputation and maschin learning \n",
    "\n",
    "by *Tatiana Klisho*, \n",
    "Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences (SLU, Alnarp)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Project discription"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Changes in sea level pressure (SLP) and sea surface temperatures (SSTs) cause long-term meteorological disturbances, that impact moisture/drought balance and thus favor the occurrence of major fire outbreaks.\n",
    "\n",
    "A better understanding of the relationship between continental-scale patterns of fire activity and modes of climate variability may explain how inter-annual to multidecadal variability in SLP and SST drives fire at the continental scale.\n",
    "\n",
    "Previous correlation analysis revealed strong linkages between climate variability and regional fire activity. Based on that, domains of potential predicability were obtained (see Figure 1). What is interesting to notice is that geographical locations where the main patterns were observed correspond to main climate oscillations, such as ENSO and NAO. This is in line with previous studies. This observation prompted me to the further investigation of correlation between aforementioned oscilations, as well as other climate phenomenon (AMO, SNAO) and fire activity, since some of them might have much more of an impact on fire prone conditions over Europe.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the further analysis following GeoComputation technics were used:\n",
    "- Data computation, by using bash scripting and Climate Data Operators (CDO) - Section 2,\n",
    "- Principal component analysis (PCA) - Section 3,\n",
    "- Experementing with different interpolation technics - Section 3,\n",
    "- Correlation Analysis - Section 4."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Section 1. Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Tis study focuses on the continental Europe, and includes European part of Russia. The geographical domain is 35$^{\\circ}$N-75$^{\\circ}$N and 20$^{\\circ}$W-50$^{\\circ}$E. The covered period is from 1980 to\n",
    "2016 year. \n",
    "\n",
    "To assess the influence of ocean/climate variability on fire prone conditions, we employed a series of different data sets:\n",
    "- The fire data are coming from The European Forest Fire Information System (EFFIS). Data are presented as country-wised annual area burned. This database includes: Portugal, Spain, France, Italy, Greece, Finland, Belarus, Latvia, Estonia, Lithuania, St.Petersburg, Norway, both northern and southern parts of Sweden, Germany, Cz.Republic,\tUkraine, Hungary, Turkey, Slovakia, Slovenia, Romania, Bulgaria, Croatia and Poland. \n",
    "- The predictors of area burned such as SST and SLP are retrieved from the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF). ECMWF provides monthly gridded reanalysis data (ERA5), with global horizontal coverage and 0.25$^{\\circ}$ x 0.25$^{\\circ}$ horizontal resolution. \n"
   ]
  },

    "## Section 2. Climate indices"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "All the climate indices (see Figure 2) were obtained by using Climate Data Operators (CDO) software and bash scripting. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2.1 ENSO 3.4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "El NioSouthern Oscillation (ENSO) - is an irregular periodic variation in SST and wind over the tropical eastern Pacific Ocean, which affects climate of much of the tropics and subtropics. \n",
    "\n",
    "The Nio 3.4 anomalies represent an average equatorial SSTs across the Pacific. The Nio 3.4 index is calculated for the region: (5N-5S, 170W-120W) and typically uses a 3-month running mean. El Nio or La  Nia events are defined when the  Nio 3.4 SSTs exceed +/- 0.4C for a period of six months or more."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%bash\n",
    "#!/bin/bash\n",
    "\n",
    "mkdir /home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SSTERA5/ENSO/\n",
    "output=\"/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SSTERA5/ENSO/\"\n",
    "dir=\"/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SSTERA5/\"\n",
    "cd $dir \n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -fldmean -timselmean,12 -sellonlatbox,120,170,-5,5 -detrend download.nc ${output}ENSOm.nc\n",
    "cdo sub ${output}ENSOm.nc -timmean ${output}ENSOm.nc ${output}ENSOa.nc\n",
    "cdo runmean,3 ${output}ENSOa.nc ${output}ENSO.nc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2.2 NAO"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO) - is the most prominent pattern of atmospheric variability in the Northern Hemisphere, especially during the cold season months (November through April). The NAO refers to a large-scale meridional oscillation of atmospheric mass between subtropical anticyclone near Azores and the subpolar low pressure system near Iceland.\n",
    "\n",
    "The NAO was calculated from the sea level pressure difference between the Subtropical (Azores) High (37.82N, 25.75W) and the Subpolar Low (65.08N,22.73W) for the November-December-January-February-March (NDJFM) period.\n",
    "\n",
    "The SLP values at each station were normalized by removing the long-term mean and by dividing by the long-term standard deviation. Normalization is used to avoid the series being dominated by the greater variability of the northern station. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%bash\n",
    "#!/bin/bash\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "mkdir /home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SLPERA5/NAO/\n",
    "output1=\"/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SLPERA5/NAO/\"\n",
    "dir1=\"/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SLPERA5/\"\n",
    "cd $dir1 \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64  -timselmean,5 -select,season=NDJFM -remapnn,lon=37.82/lat=25.75 -detrend download.nc ${output1}NAOm1.nc\n",
    "cdo -sub -fldmean ${output1}NAOm1.nc -timmean ${output1}NAOm1.nc ${output1}NAOha.nc\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -div ${output1}NAOha.nc -timstd ${output1}NAOm1.nc ${output1}NAOhn.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -timselmean,5 -select,season=NDJFM -remapnn,lon=65.08/lat=22.73 -detrend download.nc ${output1}NAOm2.nc\n",
    "cdo -sub -fldmean ${output1}NAOm2.nc -timmean ${output1}NAOm2.nc ${output1}NAOla.nc\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -div ${output1}NAOla.nc -timstd ${output1}NAOm2.nc ${output1}NAOln.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -sub ${output1}NAOhn.nc ${output1}NAOln.nc ${output1}NAO.nc\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2.3 SNAO"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Summer north atlantic oscillation (SNAO) - is the prominent atmospheric circulation patterns lookalike winter NAO, prevailing during the summer time, but a. with the action center located farther to the north (the southern node is over northwest Europe, rather than Azores region) b. with the smaller spatial extent and c. lesser amplitude than its winter counterpart. Based on the dicription, SNAO index was calculated by following the same procidure as for NAO index (see 2.2 NAO), but using summer months. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%bash\n",
    "#!/bin/bash\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "mkdir /home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SLPERA5/SNAO/\n",
    "output2=\"/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SLPERA5/SNAO/\"\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -timselmean,3 -select,season=JJA -remapnn,lon=37.82/lat=25.75 -detrend download.nc ${output2}SNAOm1.nc\n",
    "cdo -sub -fldmean ${output2}SNAOm1.nc -timmean ${output2}SNAOm1.nc ${output2}SNAOha.nc\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -div ${output2}SNAOha.nc -timstd ${output2}SNAOm1.nc ${output2}SNAOhn.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -timselmean,3 -select,season=JJA -remapnn,lon=65.08/lat=22.73 -detrend download.nc ${output2}SNAOm2.nc\n",
    "cdo -sub -fldmean ${output2}SNAOm2.nc -timmean ${output2}SNAOm2.nc ${output2}SNAOla.nc\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -div ${output2}SNAOla.nc -timstd ${output2}SNAOm2.nc ${output2}SNAOln.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -sub ${output2}SNAOhn.nc ${output2}SNAOln.nc ${output2}SNAO.nc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2.4 AMO"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) - is the theorized variability of the SST of the North Atlantic Ocean on the timescale of several decades.\n",
    "\n",
    "The AMO index was calculated by averaging summer months (JJA) Atlantic SSTs over the region 80W0E and 0N60N, followed by  subtracting the  global  average of JJA SSTs between 60S60N and then applying 10 years low-pass filtering. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%bash\n",
    "#!/bin/bash\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "mkdir /home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SSTERA5/AMO/\n",
    "output3=\"/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/SSTERA5/AMO/\"\n",
    "cd $dir\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -fldmean -yearmonmean -select,season=JJA -sellonlatbox,-80,0,0,60 -detrend download.nc ${output3}AMOm1.nc\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -sub ${output3}AMOm1.nc -timmean ${output3}AMOm1.nc ${output3}AMO1.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo -b F64 -fldmean -yearmonmean -select,season=JJA -sellonlatbox,-180,180,-60,60 -detrend download.nc ${output3}AMOm2.nc\n",
    "cdo -b F64 sub ${output3}AMOm2.nc -timmean ${output3}AMOm2.nc ${output3}AMO2.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo sub ${output3}AMO1.nc ${output3}AMO2.nc ${output3}AMO_12.nc\n",
    "\n",
    "cdo lowpass,10 ${output3}AMO_12.nc ${output3}AMO.nc "
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "## Section 3. PCA & different technics of interpolation. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "I decided to use PCA or empirical orthogonal function (EOF) analysis in order to reduce dimentionality of the fire dataset. PCA is a technique for increasing interpretability but at the same time minimizing information loss. The spatial patterns are the EOFs, and can be thought of as basis functions in terms of variance. The associated temporal projections are the pricipal components (PCs) and are the temporal coefficients of the EOF patterns."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import xarray as xr\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import csv\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "from netCDF4 import Dataset,num2date\n",
    "import cartopy.crs as crs\n",
    "import cartopy.feature as cfeature\n",
    "from scipy.interpolate import griddata  \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "path = '/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/RSLTS/Fires_detrend_a_test.csv' \n",
    "df = pd.read_csv(path,delimiter=';',skip_blank_lines=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "path1 = '/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/RSLTS/Coords.csv' \n",
    "df1 = pd.read_csv(path1,delimiter=',',skip_blank_lines=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "df2=pd.melt(df,id_vars=['Years']).rename(columns={'variable':'Country'})\n",
    "df3=pd.merge(df2,df1, how='left',on='Country')\n",
    "df3.to_csv('/home/tatiana/Documents/DATA/df3.csv',sep=';', index=False)\n",
    "df4=pd.pivot_table(df,columns='Years')\n",
    "\n",
    "####__________EOFs_____####\n",
    "\n",
    "pca = PCA(n_components=3)        #setting_the_number_of_PCs\n",
    "newpca=pca.fit_transform(df4)\n",
    "pca_1=pd.DataFrame(data = newpca, columns = ['PC_1', 'PC_2','PC_3'])\n",
    "pca_DfC=pd.DataFrame(data = newpca, columns = ['PC_1', 'PC_2','PC_3'])    #creatig_the_dataframe_ with_PCs\n",
    "pca_DfC.insert(0, \"Country\",['Belarus','Bulgaria','Croatia','Czech_Republic','Estonia','Finland','France', 'Germany','Greece','Hungary','Italy','Latvia','Lithuania','Norway', 'Petersburg','Poland', 'Portugal','Romania','Slovakia','Slovenia', 'Spain','Sweden','SwedenN','Turkey','Ukraine'], True) \n",
    "eof_f=pca_DfC.merge(df1,how='left',on='Country')\n",
    "\n",
    "####__________PCs_____####\n",
    "\n",
    "df_y=df.drop('Years',axis=1)\n",
    "pca_y = PCA(n_components=3)                \n",
    "newpca_y=pca.fit_transform(df_y)\n",
    "pca_2=pd.DataFrame(data = newpca_y, columns = ['PC_1', 'PC_2','PC_3'])  \n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Three different methods of interpolation have been tested with the aim of finding the best way of displaying data. The methods are:\n",
    "- $Cubic$ - return the value determined from a cubic spline,\n",
    "- $Linear$ - tessellate the input point set to N-D simplices, and interpolate linearly on each simplex, and\n",
    "- $Nearest$ - return the value at the data point closest to the point of interpolation. \n"
   ]
  },

    "    bar = plt.colorbar(label='First EOF')#,format='%.1f' )\n",
    "    plt.title('{}'.format(i), fontsize=16)"
